For the last workshop, we will work on a lung segmentation from CXR image¶

The data came from the Montgomery County TB dataset which consists of 58 positive and 80 normal cases

Lung segmentation masks are provide as a binary images

Download the dataset using wget command¶

This may take ~6 minutes

In [ ]:
!wget http://openi.nlm.nih.gov/imgs/collections/NLM-MontgomeryCXRSet.zip

Let's view some images to understand the data¶

Each set of data consist of 3 images: CXR, the mask for left lung, and the mask for right lung

In [ ]:
image_name = 'MCUCXR_0001_0.png'

plt.figure(figsize = (15, 5))
plt.subplot(1, 3, 1); plt.imshow(plt.imread('MontgomerySet/ManualMask/leftMask/' + image_name), cmap = 'gray')
plt.subplot(1, 3, 2); plt.imshow(plt.imread('MontgomerySet/CXR_png/' + image_name), cmap = 'gray')
plt.subplot(1, 3, 3); plt.imshow(plt.imread('MontgomerySet/ManualMask/rightMask/' + image_name), cmap = 'gray')
plt.show()

We can overlay the three images by manipulating the pixel array¶

Grayscale image is a 2D array with pixel values in [0, 1] when read with plt.imread()

In [ ]:
left_lung = plt.imread('MontgomerySet/ManualMask/leftMask/' + image_name)
right_lung = plt.imread('MontgomerySet/ManualMask/rightMask/' + image_name)
cxr = plt.imread('MontgomerySet/CXR_png/' + image_name)

print('CXR grayscale image is just a 2D array with shape:', cxr.shape)

CXR grayscale image is just a 2D array with shape: (4020, 4892)
In [ ]:
combined_mask = left_lung + right_lung
overlayed = cxr.reshape([cxr.shape[0], cxr.shape[1], 1])
overlayed = np.concatenate([overlayed, overlayed, overlayed], axis = 2)
overlayed[:, :, 2] = np.multiply(1 - combined_mask, overlayed[:, :, 2])

plt.figure(figsize = (6, 6))
plt.imshow(overlayed)
plt.show()

Define a U-Net model using MobileNetV2 as the encoder¶

Recall that U-Net's structure consists of a CNN-based encoder followed by a series of upsampling layers, with gradient shortcuts connecting each convolutional layer to the corresponding upsampling layer

Let's view the structure of MobileNetV2¶

In [ ]:
encoder = tf.keras.applications.MobileNetV2(input_shape = [224, 224, 3], weights = 'imagenet', include_top = False)
encoder.summary()

Generate a list of layer outputs for sending to the corresponding upsampling layers¶

We want the output from the last ReLU activation layer before the image size decrease each time

  1. block_1_expand_relu before the image size goes from 112 to 56
  2. block_3_expand_relu before the image size goes from 56 to 28
  3. block_6_expand_relu before the image size goes from 28 to 14
  4. block_13_expand_relu before the image size goes from 14 to 7
  5. block_16_project which is the last layer of the encoder (the rest of MobileNetV2 is for decoding outputs)
In [ ]:
encoder_output_layer_names = ['block_1_expand_relu', 'block_3_expand_relu', 'block_6_expand_relu', 'block_13_expand_relu', 'block_16_project']
encoder_outputs = [encoder.get_layer(name).output for name in encoder_output_layer_names]

Put together the whole architecture¶

In [ ]:
def generate_unet():
    inputs = layers.Input(shape = [224, 224, 3])

    skips = unet_encoder(inputs) ## outputs of the encoder, ordered from top to bottom
    x = skips[-1] ## this is the bottommost output of the encoder
    skips = reversed(skips[:-1]) ## reverse the order of the outputs from bottom to top

    for up_layer, skip in zip(decoder, skips):
        x = up_layer(x)
        x = layers.Concatenate()([x, skip]) ## connect each output from the encoder to the corresponding upsampling layer

    x = layers.Conv2DTranspose(filters = 1, kernel_size = 3, strides = 2, padding = 'same')(x) ## the last upsampling
    output = layers.Activation(activation = 'sigmoid')(x)

    return Model(inputs = inputs, outputs = output)

Prepare the dataset using TensorFlow's Dataset interface¶

Previously, we have been loading the entire datasets into the memory. But this would be impossible for large dataset. With TensorFlow's Dataset interface, we can load and process the data for each batch as we need them.

This will be our pipeline for preprocessing data¶

  1. Obtain a list of CXR file names to be loaded for this batch
  2. Load CXR images and resize them to 224x224x3
  3. Load left and right lung masks, combine them, and resize to 224x224x1
  4. Feed the resulting (CXR, mask) pairs to the model

Define a function for performing the outlined preprocessing tasks¶

In [ ]:
def load_and_resize(filename):
    try:
        bits = tf.io.read_file('MontgomerySet/CXR_png/' + filename)
        image = tf.image.decode_png(bits, channels = 3)

        image = tf.cast(image, dtype = tf.float32)
        image = image / tf.reduce_max(image, axis = None)
        dim = tf.shape(image)

        h_margin = tf.math.divide(tf.math.maximum(tf.math.subtract(dim[0], dim[1]) // 2, 0), dim[0])
        w_margin = tf.math.divide(tf.math.maximum(tf.math.subtract(dim[1], dim[0]) // 2, 0), dim[1])

        image = tf.image.crop_and_resize([image], \
                                         boxes = [[h_margin, w_margin, 1 - h_margin, 1 - w_margin]], \
                                         box_indices = [0], crop_size = [224, 224])[0, :]

        bits = tf.io.read_file('MontgomerySet/ManualMask/leftMask/' + filename)
        left_mask = tf.image.decode_png(bits, channels = 1)

        bits = tf.io.read_file('MontgomerySet/ManualMask/rightMask/' + filename)
        right_mask = tf.image.decode_png(bits, channels = 1)

        combined_mask = tf.math.add(left_mask, right_mask)
        combined_mask = tf.cast(combined_mask, dtype = tf.float32)
        combined_mask = combined_mask / tf.reduce_max(combined_mask, axis = None)

        combined_mask = tf.image.crop_and_resize([combined_mask], \
                                                 boxes = [[h_margin, w_margin, 1 - h_margin, 1 - w_margin]], \
                                                 box_indices = [0], crop_size = [224, 224])[0, :]

        return image, combined_mask

    except:
        print('cannot preprocess:', filename)

def view_overlay(cxr, mask):
    overlayed = cxr
    overlayed[:, :, 2] = np.multiply(1 - (mask[:, :, 0] > 0.5), overlayed[:, :, 2])

    plt.figure(figsize = (6, 6))
    plt.imshow(overlayed)
    plt.show()
